05623nam a22009135i 9780812209808DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979968321  a97808122098087 a10.9783/97808122098082doi  a(DE-B1597)449842  a(OCoLC)881417696  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a325.495223  aLB 562602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90572:8471 aCabot, Heath, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Doorstep of Europe :bAsylum and Citizenship in Greece /cHeath Cabot. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b5 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. The Rock of Judgment -- tAct I. Governance -- tChapter 1. European Moral Geographies -- tChapter 2. Documenting Legal Limbo -- tAct II. Judgment -- tChapter 3. Engaging Tragedy -- tChapter 4. Images of Vulnerability -- tChapter 5. Recognizing the Real Refugee -- tAct III. Citizenship -- tChapter 6. Rearticulating the Ethnos -- tChapter 7. Citizens of Athens -- tThe Machine -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGreece has shouldered a heavy burden in the global economic crisis, struggling with political and financial insecurity. Greece has also the most porous external border of the European Union, tasked with ensuring that the EU's boundaries are both "secure and humanitarian" and hosting enormous numbers of migrants and asylum seekers who arrive by land and sea. The recent leadership and fiscal crises have led to a breakdown of legal entitlements for both Greek citizens and those seeking refuge within the country's borders.On the Doorstep of Europe is an ethnographic study of the asylum system in Greece, tracing the ways asylum seekers, bureaucrats, and service providers attempt to navigate the dilemmas of governance, ethics, knowledge, and sociability that emerge through this legal process. Centering on the work of an asylum advocacy NGO in Athens, Heath Cabot explores how workers and clients grapple with predicaments endemic to Europeanization and rights-based protection. Drawing inspiration from classical Greek tragedy to highlight both the transformative potential and the violence of law, Cabot charts the structural violence effected through European governance, rights frameworks, and humanitarian intervention while also exploring how Athenian society is being remade from the inside out. She shows how, in contemporary Greece, relationships between insiders and outsiders are radically reconfigured through legal, political, and economic crises.In addition to providing a textured, on-the-ground account of the fraught context of asylum and immigration in Europe's borderlands, On the Doorstep of Europe highlights the unpredictable and transformative ways in which those in host nations navigate legal and political violence, even in contexts of inexorable duress and inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAsylum, Right ofxGreece. 0aAsylum, Right ofzGreece. 0aCitizenshipxGreece. 0aCitizenshipzGreece. 0aEmigration and immigration lawxGreece. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzGreece. 0aLegal assistance to refugeesxGreece. 0aLegal assistance to refugeeszGreece. 0aPolitical refugeesxLegal status, laws, etczGreece. 0aPolitical refugeesxLegal status, laws, etc.xGreece. 0aPolitical refugeesxLegal status, laws, etc.zGreece. 0aSocial work with immigrantsxGreece. 0aSocial work with immigrantszGreece. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Gen